\details{
A formula keyword for adding a spatial random field to a \code{gllvmTMB()}
fit, one independent field per trait, sharing a common range
parameter. The field is approximated as a Gaussian Markov random
field (GMRF) on a triangulated mesh via the \strong{Lindgren–Rue–Lindström
SPDE construction}.
\subsection{What kernel is this?}{

The SPDE construction approximates a \strong{Matérn covariance function}:

\deqn{\mathrm{cov}\bigl(\,r(\mathbf{s}_i),\, r(\mathbf{s}_j)\,\bigr) \;=\;
       \sigma^{2}\,\frac{2^{1-\nu}}{\Gamma(\nu)}\,
       \bigl(\kappa\, \|\mathbf{s}_i - \mathbf{s}_j\|\bigr)^{\nu}\,
       K_{\nu}\bigl(\kappa\, \|\mathbf{s}_i - \mathbf{s}_j\|\bigr),}

where \eqn{\nu} is the smoothness parameter, \eqn{\kappa > 0} is the
inverse-range parameter, and \eqn{K_{\nu}} is the modified Bessel
function of the second kind. \code{gllvmTMB::spatial_unique()} (and its
siblings \code{spatial_scalar()} / \code{spatial_latent()}) use
\strong{\eqn{\alpha = 2}} in the Lindgren–Rue–Lindström operator, which
(in 2 spatial dimensions) corresponds to \strong{\eqn{\nu = 1}}.

\eqn{\nu = 1} sits \emph{between} the two extremes that practitioners
often default to:\tabular{llll}{
   Kernel \tab \eqn{\nu} \tab Smoothness \tab Used by \cr
   Exponential \tab \eqn{1/2} \tab non-differentiable \tab \code{glmmTMB::exp()}, \code{metafor::SPEXP}, \verb{brms::gp(... cov="exponential")} \cr
   \strong{Matérn (this engine)} \tab \strong{\eqn{1}} \tab once mean-square differentiable \tab \code{gllvmTMB::spatial_unique()}, \code{sdmTMB::sdmTMB(spatial="on")}, \code{INLA::inla.spde2.matern()} \cr
   Matérn 3/2 \tab \eqn{3/2} \tab once differentiable \tab not implemented here \cr
   Matérn 5/2 \tab \eqn{5/2} \tab twice differentiable \tab not implemented here \cr
   Squared-exponential / Gaussian \tab \eqn{\infty} \tab infinitely smooth \tab \verb{brms::gp(... cov="exp_quad")} \cr
}


Matérn \eqn{\nu = 1} is the \emph{de facto} standard for spatial
ecological data: smooth enough to be sensible for organisms or
processes that vary continuously in space, but rough enough to
capture genuinely fine-scale variation. It is also the default of
every R-INLA and sdmTMB workflow, so \code{spatial_unique()} results
compare cleanly against those packages.
}

\subsection{How the model is parameterised}{

Each trait \eqn{t} gets its own GMRF \eqn{r_t} on the same mesh,
with:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Shared inverse-range parameter} \eqn{\kappa} (i.e. one
\code{kappa} is estimated; trait-specific ranges would require a
per-trait \code{kappa}, which is not currently implemented). The
\emph{practical} range is \eqn{\sqrt{8}/\kappa}, the distance at
which correlation drops to ~0.13.
\item \strong{Per-trait precision parameter} \eqn{\tau_t}. The marginal
variance is
\eqn{\sigma_t^{\,2} = 1 / (4\pi\,\kappa^{2}\,\tau_t^{\,2})}.
}

On the precision side the SPDE/GMRF prior is
\eqn{\mathbf{Q}_t \;=\; \tau_t^{\,2}\,(\kappa^{4}\,\mathbf{M}_0
                         + 2\kappa^{2}\,\mathbf{M}_1
                         + \mathbf{M}_2)},
where \eqn{\mathbf{M}_0, \mathbf{M}_1, \mathbf{M}_2} are the
fmesher-built finite-element mass and stiffness matrices. The
resulting matrix is sparse (each row has a small constant number of
non-zeros), so TMB's sparse Cholesky scales linearly with mesh
size — that's the speed advantage over \code{glmmTMB::exp()}'s dense
\eqn{n \times n} covariance matrix
(see \code{vignette("spde-vs-glmmTMB")} for the live benchmark).
}

\subsection{Reduced-rank spatial loadings (\code{spatial_latent()})}{

\code{\link[=spatial_unique]{spatial_unique()}} gives one \emph{independent} field per trait. The
reduced-rank analogue — \eqn{K} shared spatial fields driving all
\eqn{T} traits via a \eqn{T \times K} loading matrix
\eqn{\boldsymbol\Lambda_{\mathrm{spa}}}, exactly what \code{\link[=phylo_latent]{phylo_latent()}}
does for phylogeny — is the canonical \code{\link[=spatial_latent]{spatial_latent()}} keyword.
Internally the same SPDE engine fits both: when \code{spatial_latent()} is
active the template's \code{spde_lv_k} switch flips on, swapping the
per-trait \eqn{\boldsymbol\omega_t} for a packed
\eqn{\boldsymbol\Lambda_{\mathrm{spa}}} multiplied into K shared
fields \eqn{\boldsymbol\omega_k} (each given the same Matérn prior
as the per-trait fields, with \eqn{\tau} absorbed into
\eqn{\boldsymbol\Lambda_{\mathrm{spa}}} for identifiability — the
standard rr / \code{\link[=phylo_latent]{phylo_latent()}} convention).
}

\subsection{Usage}{

Inside a \code{gllvmTMB()} formula, paired with a mesh built from the
coordinate columns of \code{data}:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{df$pos <- glmmTMB::numFactor(df$lon, df$lat)   # only if comparing
mesh   <- make_mesh(df, c("lon", "lat"), cutoff = 0.07)
fit    <- gllvmTMB(
  value ~ 0 + trait + spatial_unique(0 + trait | coords),
  data = df, mesh = mesh
)
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

The canonical \code{0 + trait | coords} syntax (LHS = the trait factor,
RHS = the \code{coords} placeholder) means "one independent SPDE field per
level of \code{trait}, indexed by the coordinate columns named in \code{mesh}".
The actual coordinate column names live in the \code{mesh} object (see
\code{\link[=make_mesh]{make_mesh()}}); the \code{coords} token in the formula is just a
placeholder. The pre-0.1.4 orientation \code{coords | trait} is also
accepted but emits a one-shot lifecycle deprecation warning per
session; see \code{\link[=spatial_unique]{spatial_unique()}}.
}
}
\examples{
\dontrun{
set.seed(2025)
s <- simulate_site_trait(
  n_sites = 60, n_species = 1, n_traits = 3, mean_species_per_site = 1,
  spatial_range = 0.3, sigma2_spa = rep(0.4, 3), seed = 1
)
df   <- s$data
mesh <- make_mesh(df, c("lon", "lat"), cutoff = 0.07)
fit  <- gllvmTMB(value ~ 0 + trait + spatial_unique(0 + trait | coords),
                 data = df, mesh = mesh)
fit$report$kappa            # inverse-range parameter
sqrt(8) / fit$report$kappa  # practical range
}
}
